to a temperature of 2.955 plus
or minus 0.017 K. The size

00:30:00.040 --> 00:30:02.480
of the vertical bars
there are the error

00:30:02.480 --> 00:30:06.970
bars that the
experimenters found.

00:30:06.970 --> 00:30:31.560
And 0.3 was t equals 3.175
plus or minus 0.027 K.

00:30:31.560 --> 00:30:33.780
So these were higher
temperatures then

00:30:33.780 --> 00:30:38.490
the 2.7 that fit the lower
part of the spectrum.

00:30:38.490 --> 00:30:40.640
And very, very small error bars.

00:30:43.250 --> 00:30:45.330
So this data came out in 1987.

00:30:45.330 --> 00:30:50.700
And, in truth, nobody knew
what to make out of it.

00:30:50.700 --> 00:30:54.730
The experimental group were
well aware that this was not

00:30:54.730 --> 00:30:58.530
what people wanted them to find.

00:30:58.530 --> 00:31:01.560
And they certainly
examined their data

00:31:01.560 --> 00:31:04.880
very carefully to figure at
what could have conceivably gone

00:31:04.880 --> 00:31:05.930
wrong.

00:31:05.930 --> 00:31:08.390
And they were going
around the country

00:31:08.390 --> 00:31:09.650
giving talks about this.

00:31:09.650 --> 00:31:12.250
And I heard one or
two of them in which

00:31:12.250 --> 00:31:15.180
they described how surprised
they were by the results,

00:31:15.180 --> 00:31:19.410
but emphasized that they
analyzed the experiment very,

00:31:19.410 --> 00:31:23.420
very carefully and couldn't
find anything wrong with it.

00:31:23.420 --> 00:31:26.250
And this was the
situation for awhile.

00:31:26.250 --> 00:31:29.600
I should point out that I think
this point number three is

00:31:29.600 --> 00:31:34.020
something like 16 standard
deviations off of the theory.

00:31:34.020 --> 00:31:37.220
And usually when somebody
makes a measurement that's

00:31:37.220 --> 00:31:39.930
three or four standard
deviations off of your theory,

00:31:39.930 --> 00:31:41.950
you really start to worry.

00:31:41.950 --> 00:31:46.910
16 standard deviations is
certainly a bit extreme.

00:31:46.910 --> 00:31:53.095
Nonetheless, nobody had any
good explanation for this.

00:31:53.095 --> 00:31:55.220
So, well, different people
had different attitudes.

00:31:55.220 --> 00:31:57.470
There were some people who
tried to construct theories

00:31:57.470 --> 00:31:59.260
that would account for this.

00:31:59.260 --> 00:32:04.870
And there were others who
waited for it to go away.

00:32:04.870 --> 00:32:06.290
I'm pretty sure
I was among those

00:32:06.290 --> 00:32:11.960
who waited for it to go
away, and we were right.

00:32:11.960 --> 00:32:15.240
So the next important
piece of data

00:32:15.240 --> 00:32:17.770
came from the first
satellite dedicated

00:32:17.770 --> 00:32:21.260
to measuring the cosmic
background radiation.

00:32:21.260 --> 00:32:26.654
The famous COBE Satellite--
Cosmic Background Explorer-- I

00:32:26.654 --> 00:32:28.320
guess I didn't write
down the name here.

00:32:28.320 --> 00:32:29.370
Oh, it's in the title.

00:32:29.370 --> 00:32:32.250
Preliminary measurement of the
cosmic microwave background

00:32:32.250 --> 00:32:35.440
spectrum by the Cosmic
Background Explorer,

00:32:35.440 --> 00:32:37.290
COBE Satellite.

00:32:37.290 --> 00:32:39.820
So COBE was the first
satellite dedicated

00:32:39.820 --> 00:32:43.605
to measuring the cosmic
background radiation.

00:32:43.605 --> 00:32:48.770
It was launched in 1989,
I guess, and released

00:32:48.770 --> 00:32:53.980
its first data in
January of 1990.

00:32:53.980 --> 00:32:58.700
Back in those days there
was no internet or archive.

00:32:58.700 --> 00:33:01.510
So you may or may not know that
the way physics results were

00:33:01.510 --> 00:33:03.200
first announced
to the world were

00:33:03.200 --> 00:33:06.510
in the form of what were
called pre-prints, which

00:33:06.510 --> 00:33:12.130
were essentially xeroxed copies
of the paper that were sent out

00:33:12.130 --> 00:33:14.220
to a mailing list.

00:33:14.220 --> 00:33:16.870
Typically, I think,
institutions had mailing lists

00:33:16.870 --> 00:33:20.260
of maybe 100 other institutions.

00:33:20.260 --> 00:33:24.930
And every physics department
had a pre-print library

00:33:24.930 --> 00:33:28.510
that people can go to and
find these pre-prints.

00:33:28.510 --> 00:33:30.940
So this is the COBE pre-print.

00:33:30.940 --> 00:33:35.560
90-01, the first
pre-print from 1990.

00:33:35.560 --> 00:33:36.770
And this is the data.

00:33:46.080 --> 00:33:49.600
So it is kind of
breathtaking, I think.

00:33:49.600 --> 00:33:54.130
It suddenly changed the entire
field, and in some sense

00:33:54.130 --> 00:33:55.764
really change cosmology
for the field.

00:33:55.764 --> 00:33:57.680
Where we only had
approximate ideas of the way

00:33:57.680 --> 00:34:05.530
things worked, to suddenly
having a really precise science

00:34:05.530 --> 00:34:08.960
in which precise
measurements could be made,

00:34:08.960 --> 00:34:10.849
and cleared up the
issue of the radiation.

00:34:13.969 --> 00:34:19.219
It wasn't just a mess like this,
or a terrible fit like that,

00:34:19.219 --> 00:34:23.460
but a fantastically good fit.

00:34:23.460 --> 00:34:30.320
Really nailing the radiation
as having a thermal spectrum.

00:34:30.320 --> 00:34:34.360
So the history is that John
Mather presented this data

00:34:34.360 --> 00:34:40.179
at the January 1990 American
Physical Society meeting,

00:34:40.179 --> 00:34:43.870
and was given a
standing ovation.

00:34:43.870 --> 00:34:47.150
And he later won the
Nobel Prize for this work.

00:34:47.150 --> 00:34:49.490
He was the head of the team
that brought this data.

00:34:49.490 --> 00:34:53.000
He won the Nobel Prize in
2006 along with George Smoot,

00:34:53.000 --> 00:34:55.719
who was responsible for one
of the other experiments

00:34:55.719 --> 00:34:57.761
on the COBE satellite.

00:34:57.761 --> 00:34:58.260
Yes?

00:34:58.260 --> 00:34:59.801
AUDIENCE: So do we
know what happened

00:34:59.801 --> 00:35:01.120
with the other measurements?

00:35:01.120 --> 00:35:01.856
PROFESSOR: To tell
you the truth,

00:35:01.856 --> 00:35:03.390
I don't think the
other measurements

00:35:03.390 --> 00:35:05.330
ever-- the other people
ever really published

00:35:05.330 --> 00:35:06.371
what they think happened.

00:35:06.371 --> 00:35:10.280
But the widespread rumor,
which I imagine is true,

00:35:10.280 --> 00:35:14.850
is that they were seeing
their own rocket exhaust.

00:35:14.850 --> 00:35:19.000
And there were, I think,
some arguments going on

00:35:19.000 --> 00:35:23.260
between the Americans
and the Japanese,

00:35:23.260 --> 00:35:27.694
with the Americans more or less
accusing the Japanese of not

00:35:27.694 --> 00:35:29.610
really telling them how
the rocket was set up.

00:35:33.070 --> 00:35:33.580
Yes?

00:35:33.580 --> 00:35:36.256
AUDIENCE: Are the error bars
plugged on those points,

00:35:36.256 --> 00:35:37.980
or is it just that good?

00:35:37.980 --> 00:35:39.605
PROFESSOR: Those
are the error bars?

00:35:39.605 --> 00:35:40.146
AUDIENCE: OK.

00:35:47.130 --> 00:35:51.860
PROFESSOR: And even
more spectacular,

00:35:51.860 --> 00:35:54.210
a couple years later,
I guess it was-- this

00:35:54.210 --> 00:35:56.710
was actually just based on nine
minutes of data or something

00:35:56.710 --> 00:35:58.080
like that.

00:35:58.080 --> 00:36:01.840
But a couple years later they
published their full data set,

00:36:01.840 --> 00:36:08.380
where the size of the error bars
were reduced by a factor of 10.

00:36:08.380 --> 00:36:11.649
And still a perfect fit.

00:36:11.649 --> 00:36:13.190
They didn't even
know how to plot it,

00:36:13.190 --> 00:36:14.814
so I think they
plotted the same graph,

00:36:14.814 --> 00:36:16.910
and said the error
bars are a factor of 10

00:36:16.910 --> 00:36:19.385
smalled than what's shown.

00:36:19.385 --> 00:36:20.295
It was gorgeous.

00:36:34.400 --> 00:36:37.520
So I think I forgot to tell you
what the spectrum is supposed

00:36:37.520 --> 00:36:39.975
to look like exactly.

00:36:39.975 --> 00:36:41.840
And this is just
a formula that I

00:36:41.840 --> 00:36:44.420
want you to understand
the meaning of, but not

00:36:44.420 --> 00:36:46.830
the derivation of.

00:36:46.830 --> 00:36:53.378
We-- as with the other stat mech
results that we're relying on,

00:36:53.378 --> 00:36:56.810
we're going to relegate their
derivation to the stat mech

00:36:56.810 --> 00:36:59.740
course that you either
have taken or will take.

00:36:59.740 --> 00:37:01.610
But the spectrum is
completely determined

00:37:01.610 --> 00:37:04.830
because the principle
of thermal equilibrium

00:37:04.830 --> 00:37:07.890
is sort of absolute in
statistical mechanics.

00:37:07.890 --> 00:37:11.510
And in order for a
black-body radiating

00:37:11.510 --> 00:37:15.120
object to be in
thermal equilibrium

00:37:15.120 --> 00:37:19.340
with an environment
at that temperature,

00:37:19.340 --> 00:37:22.430
it has to have not only the
right emission rate but also

00:37:22.430 --> 00:37:23.666
the right spectrum.

00:37:23.666 --> 00:37:25.040
If the spectrum
weren't right you

00:37:25.040 --> 00:37:26.581
could imagine putting
in filters that

00:37:26.581 --> 00:37:30.130
would trap in some frequencies
and let out others.

00:37:30.130 --> 00:37:32.860
And then you would move away
from thermal equilibrium

00:37:32.860 --> 00:37:35.750
if the spectrum were right
or wrong because you'd

00:37:35.750 --> 00:37:38.880
be trapping in more
radiation-- you could arrange

00:37:38.880 --> 00:37:44.030
for the filters to trap in more
radiation than they are letting

00:37:44.030 --> 00:37:45.970
out.

00:37:45.970 --> 00:37:51.400
So the spectrum is calculable.

00:37:51.400 --> 00:37:58.995
And in terms of-- I guess
this is energy density.

00:37:58.995 --> 00:38:01.210
I have to admit, I usually
call energy density u

00:38:01.210 --> 00:38:03.070
and in these notes
here it's called rho.

00:38:09.520 --> 00:38:12.440
We'll figure out the units after
I write it down and make sure

00:38:12.440 --> 00:38:14.750
that it is energy density.

00:38:14.750 --> 00:38:21.890
Rho sub nu of nu d nu,
means-- with this product

00:38:21.890 --> 00:38:27.340
it means the total energy
density, energy per volume,

00:38:27.340 --> 00:38:30.891
per frequency interval, d
nu-- well, it's times d nu,

00:38:30.891 --> 00:38:32.390
so if you multiply
by times nu, this

00:38:32.390 --> 00:38:36.050
is the total energy for
frequencies between nu and nu

00:38:36.050 --> 00:38:38.220
plus d nu.

00:38:38.220 --> 00:38:51.770
And the formula is 16 pi
squared h bar nu cubed, divided

00:38:51.770 --> 00:39:07.980
by c cubed times 1 over e to
the 2 pi h bar nu over kt,

00:39:07.980 --> 00:39:11.290
minus 1 d nu.

00:39:26.480 --> 00:39:26.980
OK.

00:39:26.980 --> 00:39:28.896
And actually, the unit's
not that transparent.

00:39:28.896 --> 00:39:32.800
I believe this is energy
density and not mass density.

00:39:32.800 --> 00:39:37.350
But maybe I'll make sure of
that and let you know next time.

00:39:39.880 --> 00:39:41.610
And this is what
produces that curve

00:39:41.610 --> 00:39:43.310
that you saw on the slides.

00:39:47.890 --> 00:39:49.660
I've included the
subscript nu here

00:39:49.660 --> 00:39:52.550
to indicate that it's the number
which, when you multiply it

00:39:52.550 --> 00:39:56.640
by d nu, gives you the energy
density between nu and nu

00:39:56.640 --> 00:39:58.230
plus d nu.

00:39:58.230 --> 00:40:00.110
If instead you wanted
to know the energy

00:40:00.110 --> 00:40:04.690
density between lambda
and lambda plus d lambda,

00:40:04.690 --> 00:40:06.620
there'd be a kinematic
factor that you'd

00:40:06.620 --> 00:40:10.660
have to put in here-- the factor
that relates d lambda to d nu.

00:40:10.660 --> 00:40:15.460
And you could imagine
working that out.

00:40:15.460 --> 00:40:17.090
I might add that,
in Weinberg's book,

00:40:17.090 --> 00:40:22.772
he actually plots
both sub lambda of nu.

00:40:22.772 --> 00:40:24.980
So his curve looks somewhat
different than the curves

00:40:24.980 --> 00:40:26.492
that I showed you.

00:40:26.492 --> 00:40:27.950
This is not exactly
the same thing.

00:40:34.910 --> 00:40:39.050
Now, what this extremely
accurately black-body curve

00:40:39.050 --> 00:40:42.480
proves is that the
early universe really

00:40:42.480 --> 00:40:46.970
was very accurately in
thermal equilibrium.

00:40:46.970 --> 00:40:50.754
And that can only happen if the
early universe was very dense.

00:40:50.754 --> 00:40:52.420
And of course, our
model of the universe

00:40:52.420 --> 00:40:54.090
goes back to infinite density.

00:40:54.090 --> 00:40:55.860
So the model predicts
that it should

00:40:55.860 --> 00:40:57.880
be in thermal equilibrium.

00:40:57.880 --> 00:41:01.530
But in particular, the
numbers that we have here,

00:41:01.530 --> 00:41:03.610
if you ask how much could
you change the model

00:41:03.610 --> 00:41:08.040
and still expect these
curves the answer

00:41:08.040 --> 00:41:13.110
is roughly that, all of the
important energy-releasing

00:41:13.110 --> 00:41:16.080
processes have to have
happened before about one

00:41:16.080 --> 00:41:18.520
year after the Big Bang.

00:41:18.520 --> 00:41:20.540
Anything that happened
after one year

00:41:20.540 --> 00:41:22.670
would still show
up as some glitch

00:41:22.670 --> 00:41:26.110
in the black-body spectrum.

00:41:26.110 --> 00:41:30.030
So the big bag model really
is confirmed back to about one

00:41:30.030 --> 00:41:33.350
year on the basis of
this precise measurement

00:41:33.350 --> 00:41:35.974
of the spectrum of the
cosmic background radiation.

00:41:35.974 --> 00:41:37.890
And the COBE measurement
is still, by the way,

00:41:37.890 --> 00:41:39.860
the best measurement
of the spectrum.

00:41:39.860 --> 00:41:41.860
We've had other very
important experiments,

00:41:41.860 --> 00:41:43.500
that we'll talk
about later, which

00:41:43.500 --> 00:41:47.230
measure the non-uniformity
of the black-body radiation.

00:41:47.230 --> 00:41:49.600
Which is very small,
but nonetheless very,

00:41:49.600 --> 00:41:51.690
very important [? effect. ?]

00:41:51.690 --> 00:41:56.460
So we've had WMAP
and now Planck which

00:41:56.460 --> 00:41:59.790
have been dedicated to
measuring the anisotropies

00:41:59.790 --> 00:42:00.870
of the radiation.

00:42:00.870 --> 00:42:02.490
COBE also made
initial measurements

00:42:02.490 --> 00:42:04.210
of the anisotropies.

00:42:04.210 --> 00:42:06.420
And we'll be talking
about anisotropies later

00:42:06.420 --> 00:42:08.380
in the course.

00:42:08.380 --> 00:42:09.170
Yes?

00:42:09.170 --> 00:42:12.337
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE].

00:42:12.337 --> 00:42:13.045
PROFESSOR: Sorry?

00:42:13.045 --> 00:42:14.930
AUDIENCE: The units
of the right-hand side

00:42:14.930 --> 00:42:16.050
are energy density.

00:42:16.050 --> 00:42:16.370
PROFESSOR: Energy density.

00:42:16.370 --> 00:42:16.870
OK.

00:42:16.870 --> 00:42:17.380
Thanks.

00:42:17.380 --> 00:42:17.880
OK.

00:42:17.880 --> 00:42:18.380
Good.

00:42:18.380 --> 00:42:20.100
So my words were right.

00:42:20.100 --> 00:42:22.169
I should have called
it u, I think,

00:42:22.169 --> 00:42:23.835
to be consistent with
my usual notation.

00:42:31.340 --> 00:42:31.840
Thanks.

00:42:36.050 --> 00:42:36.550
OK.

00:42:36.550 --> 00:42:37.966
Any other questions
about the CMB?

00:42:37.966 --> 00:42:41.230
Because if not, we're going
to change gears completely

00:42:41.230 --> 00:42:46.800
and start talking about one of
the other crucially important

00:42:46.800 --> 00:42:52.940
observational discoveries in
cosmology in the last 20 years.

00:43:01.571 --> 00:43:02.070
OK.

00:43:02.070 --> 00:43:03.590
So what I want to
talk about next

00:43:03.590 --> 00:43:10.040
is the very important
discovery originally made

00:43:10.040 --> 00:43:19.584
in 1998-- also resulting
in a Nobel Prize--

00:43:19.584 --> 00:43:21.000
that the universe
is accelerating.

00:43:35.110 --> 00:43:36.940
And this was a
discovery that involved

00:43:36.940 --> 00:43:40.030
two experimental groups,
and a total of something

00:43:40.030 --> 00:43:43.960
like 52 astronomers
between the two groups.

00:43:43.960 --> 00:43:46.980
Which actually meant that--
I'm exaggerating slightly,

00:43:46.980 --> 00:43:47.560
I suppose.

00:43:47.560 --> 00:43:49.544
But it really
involved the majority

00:43:49.544 --> 00:43:51.710
of the astronomers of the
world, and therefore there

00:43:51.710 --> 00:43:53.918
weren't a lot of astronomers
to argue with them about

00:43:53.918 --> 00:43:57.220
whether or not the
result was right.

00:43:57.220 --> 00:43:59.110
But there still
was some argument.

00:43:59.110 --> 00:44:03.350
The announcement was initially
made at a AAS meeting

00:44:03.350 --> 00:44:10.250
in January of 1998 by--
which group was first?

00:44:10.250 --> 00:44:18.570
I think that was the High-Z
Supernova-- where are they?

00:44:18.570 --> 00:44:19.070
Yeah.

00:44:19.070 --> 00:44:22.220
That was the High-Z
Supernova Search Team.

00:44:22.220 --> 00:44:26.080
And then there was also a group
largely based at Berkeley.

00:44:26.080 --> 00:44:29.670
The High-Z Supernova Search Team
was actually fairly diffused,

00:44:29.670 --> 00:44:33.190
although based to some
extent at Harvard.

00:44:33.190 --> 00:44:35.710
And the Supernova
Cosmology Project

00:44:35.710 --> 00:44:38.600
was based rather
squarely in Berkeley,

00:44:38.600 --> 00:44:42.260
headed by Saul Perlmutter.

00:44:42.260 --> 00:44:43.700
And they both agreed.

00:44:43.700 --> 00:44:47.390
And what they found
was, by looking

00:44:47.390 --> 00:44:54.510
at distant supernovae of a
particular type-- type 1a--

00:44:54.510 --> 00:45:00.530
they were able to use these
supernovae as standard candles.

00:45:00.530 --> 00:45:02.530
And because supernovae
are brighter

00:45:02.530 --> 00:45:06.320
than other standard candles
that had been studied earlier

00:45:06.320 --> 00:45:10.660
in history, they were able to go
out to much greater distances.

00:45:10.660 --> 00:45:14.610
And that means to look
much further back in time

00:45:14.610 --> 00:45:17.520
than previous studies.

00:45:17.520 --> 00:45:21.420
And what they discovered
was that the expansion rate

00:45:21.420 --> 00:45:23.680
of the universe
today was actually

00:45:23.680 --> 00:45:27.600
faster, and not slower,
than the expansion rate

00:45:27.600 --> 00:45:31.080
about five billion years ago.

00:45:31.080 --> 00:45:36.030
And that was a big shock because
until then everybody expected

00:45:36.030 --> 00:45:38.850
that gravity would
be slowing down

00:45:38.850 --> 00:45:41.430
the expansion of the universe.

00:45:41.430 --> 00:45:45.710
And when these guys started
to make these measurements

00:45:45.710 --> 00:45:48.730
they were just simply
trying to figure out

00:45:48.730 --> 00:45:52.330
how fast the universe
was slowing down.

00:45:52.330 --> 00:45:55.730
And they were shocked to
discover that it was not

00:45:55.730 --> 00:46:00.400
slowing down, but
instead speeding up.

00:46:00.400 --> 00:46:02.420
Initially there was some
controversy about it.

00:46:02.420 --> 00:46:06.055
People did try to invent other
explanations for this data.

00:46:09.130 --> 00:46:14.240
But the data has, in fact, held
up for the period from 1998

00:46:14.240 --> 00:46:15.320
to the present.

00:46:15.320 --> 00:46:20.000
And in fact, it has been
strongly supported by evidence

00:46:20.000 --> 00:46:23.040
from these anisotropies in the
cosmic microwave background

00:46:23.040 --> 00:46:26.070
radiation, which we'll
be talking about later.

00:46:26.070 --> 00:46:28.330
But it turns out, you can
get a lot of information

00:46:28.330 --> 00:46:33.270
from these anisotropies in the
cosmic background radiation.

00:46:33.270 --> 00:46:36.820
So the picture now is
really quite secure,

00:46:36.820 --> 00:46:41.670
that the acceleration-- the
expansion of the universe

00:46:41.670 --> 00:46:47.790
is actually accelerating,
and not decelerating.

00:46:47.790 --> 00:46:49.950
And the simplest
explanation for that,

00:46:49.950 --> 00:46:54.290
which is the one that--
well, certainly because it's

00:46:54.290 --> 00:46:57.330
the most plausible, and the one
that most of us take seriously,

00:46:57.330 --> 00:46:59.913
and it's the only one that fits
the data extraordinarily well.

00:46:59.913 --> 00:47:03.410
So we've not seen any reason
not to use this explanation.

00:47:03.410 --> 00:47:07.690
The simplest explanation is
that there's a nonzero energy

00:47:07.690 --> 00:47:11.360
density to the
vacuum, which is also

00:47:11.360 --> 00:47:13.400
what Einstein called the
cosmological constant.

00:47:16.140 --> 00:47:17.970
So we should begin
by writing down

00:47:17.970 --> 00:47:23.245
the equations that
describe this issue.

00:47:44.060 --> 00:47:46.910
So we've learned how to write
down the second order Friedmann

00:47:46.910 --> 00:47:55.972
equation, which
describes how the scale

00:47:55.972 --> 00:47:57.430
factor of the
universe accelerates.

00:48:05.330 --> 00:48:09.730
And on the right-hand side,
once we included materials

00:48:09.730 --> 00:48:12.480
with nonzero
pressures, we discover

00:48:12.480 --> 00:48:14.860
that we need on the
right-hand side, rho plus 3 p,

00:48:14.860 --> 00:48:17.810
over c squared--
excuse me-- times a.

00:48:22.860 --> 00:48:25.790
Now when the cosmological
constant was born,

00:48:25.790 --> 00:48:29.720
was when Einstein
first turned his theory

00:48:29.720 --> 00:48:32.730
of general relativity
to cosmology.

00:48:32.730 --> 00:48:36.700
Einstein invented the theory
of general relativity in 1916.

00:48:36.700 --> 00:48:40.210
And just one year
later, in 1917,

00:48:40.210 --> 00:48:42.370
he was applying it to
the universe as a whole

00:48:42.370 --> 00:48:45.800
to see if he could get
a cosmological model

00:48:45.800 --> 00:48:49.370
consistent with
general relativity.

00:48:49.370 --> 00:48:55.860
Einstein at that point was
under the misconception

00:48:55.860 --> 00:48:59.790
that the universe was static,
as Newton had also thought,

00:48:59.790 --> 00:49:02.260
and as far as we
know, as everybody

00:49:02.260 --> 00:49:06.830
between Newton and
Einstein thought.

00:49:06.830 --> 00:49:11.350
If you look up at the stars, the
universe looks pretty static.

00:49:11.350 --> 00:49:13.845
And people took
this very seriously.

00:49:13.845 --> 00:49:16.220
In hindsight, it's a little
hard to know why they took it

00:49:16.220 --> 00:49:19.490
so seriously, but they did.

00:49:19.490 --> 00:49:25.820
So when Einstein
discovered this equation

00:49:25.820 --> 00:49:27.990
he was assuming that
the universe consisted

00:49:27.990 --> 00:49:30.210
of basically
non-relativistic stuff.

00:49:30.210 --> 00:49:33.300
Stars are essentially
non-relativistic hunks

00:49:33.300 --> 00:49:35.220
of matter.

00:49:35.220 --> 00:49:37.300
So he thought that
rho would be positive,

00:49:37.300 --> 00:49:41.390
the effective pressure
would be zero.

00:49:41.390 --> 00:49:45.400
And he immediately
noticed that this equation

00:49:45.400 --> 00:49:49.240
would imply that the
scale factor would

00:49:49.240 --> 00:49:51.800
have a negative acceleration.

00:49:51.800 --> 00:49:54.300
So that if you tried to
set up a static universe

00:49:54.300 --> 00:49:57.170
it would instantly collapse.

00:49:57.170 --> 00:50:00.370
And as we talked
about earlier, Newton

00:50:00.370 --> 00:50:03.910
had talked himself out
of that conclusion.

00:50:03.910 --> 00:50:06.090
And I think the real
difference, as I think we also

00:50:06.090 --> 00:50:08.850
talked about earlier, was
that Newton was thinking

00:50:08.850 --> 00:50:12.310
of the law of gravity as
an action at a distance,

00:50:12.310 --> 00:50:14.390
where you determine the
total force on something

00:50:14.390 --> 00:50:18.850
by integrating the forces
caused by all other masses.

00:50:18.850 --> 00:50:21.520
And then things get complicated
and divergent, actually,

00:50:21.520 --> 00:50:24.220
for an infinite,
static universe.

00:50:24.220 --> 00:50:26.500
And Newton managed
to convince himself

00:50:26.500 --> 00:50:30.540
that you could have a static
universe of that type,

00:50:30.540 --> 00:50:32.540
a statement that we now
consider to be incorrect

00:50:32.540 --> 00:50:35.800
even in the context of
Newtonian mechanics.

00:50:35.800 --> 00:50:38.279
But this fact that
it's incorrect even

00:50:38.279 --> 00:50:39.820
in the context of
Newtonian mechanics

00:50:39.820 --> 00:50:42.230
was really not discovered
until Einstein wrote down

00:50:42.230 --> 00:50:43.520
this equation.

00:50:43.520 --> 00:50:50.090
And then Einstein himself
also gave a Newtonian argument

00:50:50.090 --> 00:50:53.860
showing that, at least with
a modern interpretation

00:50:53.860 --> 00:50:55.050
of Newtonian mechanics.

00:50:55.050 --> 00:50:56.970
It doesn't work in
Newtonian gravity

00:50:56.970 --> 00:50:59.940
either to have a
static universe.

00:50:59.940 --> 00:51:05.440
But Einstein was still convinced
that the universe was static.

00:51:05.440 --> 00:51:12.049
And he realized that he could
modify his field equations--

00:51:12.049 --> 00:51:13.840
the equations that we
have not written down

00:51:13.840 --> 00:51:17.190
in this course, the equations
that describe how matter create

00:51:17.190 --> 00:51:22.280
gravitational fields--
by adding a new term

00:51:22.280 --> 00:51:31.195
with a new coefficient in front
of it which he called lambda.

00:52:00.580 --> 00:52:05.060
And this extra
term, lambda, could

00:52:05.060 --> 00:52:09.320
produce a kind of a universal
gravitational repulsion.

00:52:09.320 --> 00:52:12.330
And he realised he had to adjust
the constant to be just right

00:52:12.330 --> 00:52:15.050
to balance the amount of
matter in the universe.

00:52:15.050 --> 00:52:17.840
But he didn't let
that bother him.

00:52:17.840 --> 00:52:19.690
And if he adjusted
it to be just right,

00:52:19.690 --> 00:52:21.820
and the universe was
perfectly homogeneous,

00:52:21.820 --> 00:52:23.770
he could arrange
for it to balance

00:52:23.770 --> 00:52:27.375
the standard force of gravity.

00:52:27.375 --> 00:52:29.500
We can understand what
lambda does to the equations

00:52:29.500 --> 00:52:31.625
because it does, in fact,
have a simple description

00:52:31.625 --> 00:52:34.240
in terms of things that we have
discussed and do understand.

00:52:34.240 --> 00:52:36.020
That is, you could
think of lambda

00:52:36.020 --> 00:52:41.540
as simply corresponding to
a vacuum energy density.

00:52:41.540 --> 00:52:45.470
Einstein did not
make that connection.

00:52:45.470 --> 00:52:48.790
And not being an
historian of science,

00:52:48.790 --> 00:52:50.800
I can speculate
as much as I want.

00:52:50.800 --> 00:52:54.420
So my speculation is that,
the reason this did not

00:52:54.420 --> 00:52:57.250
occur to Einstein
is that Einstein

00:52:57.250 --> 00:53:00.840
was a fully classical
physicist who was not

00:53:00.840 --> 00:53:03.390
at this time or
maybe never accepting

00:53:03.390 --> 00:53:04.669
the notions of quantum theory.

00:53:04.669 --> 00:53:06.210
And in any case,
quantum field theory

00:53:06.210 --> 00:53:08.940
was still far in the future.

00:53:08.940 --> 00:53:13.130
So in classical physics the
vacuum is just plain empty.

00:53:13.130 --> 00:53:15.540
And if the vacuum
is just plain empty

00:53:15.540 --> 00:53:18.760
it shouldn't have
any energy density.

00:53:18.760 --> 00:53:21.060
The quantum field theory
picture of the vacuum,

00:53:21.060 --> 00:53:24.860
however, is vastly more complex.

00:53:24.860 --> 00:53:28.250
So to a modern quantum
field theory-oriented

00:53:28.250 --> 00:53:32.090
theoretical physicist
the vacuum has

00:53:32.090 --> 00:53:35.260
particle, anti-particle pairs
appearing and disappearing

00:53:35.260 --> 00:53:36.890
all the time.

00:53:36.890 --> 00:53:38.970
We are now convinced
that there's also

00:53:38.970 --> 00:53:43.330
this Higgs field that has
even a nonzero mean value

00:53:43.330 --> 00:53:44.850
in the vacuum.

00:53:44.850 --> 00:53:47.180
So the vacuum is a
very complicated state

00:53:47.180 --> 00:53:48.910
which, if anything
characterizes it,

00:53:48.910 --> 00:53:52.790
it's simply the state of
lowest possible energy density.

00:53:52.790 --> 00:53:56.120
But because of, basically,
the uncertainty principles

00:53:56.120 --> 00:53:58.830
of quantum mechanics, the
lowest possible energy density

00:53:58.830 --> 00:54:00.810
does not mean that all
the fields are just zero

00:54:00.810 --> 00:54:02.210
and stay zero.

00:54:02.210 --> 00:54:05.226
They're constantly
fluctuating as they must

00:54:05.226 --> 00:54:07.100
according to the
uncertainty principle, which

00:54:07.100 --> 00:54:08.955
applies to fields
as well particles.

00:54:11.490 --> 00:54:15.220
So we have no reason
anymore to expect the energy

00:54:15.220 --> 00:54:18.010
density of the
vacuum to be zero.

00:54:18.010 --> 00:54:20.490
So from a modern perspective
it's very natural

00:54:20.490 --> 00:54:24.110
to simply equate the idea
of the cosmological constant

00:54:24.110 --> 00:54:27.430
to the idea of a nonzero
vacuum energy density.

00:54:27.430 --> 00:54:31.050
And there are some
unit differences-- just

00:54:31.050 --> 00:54:34.110
constants related to
the historical way

00:54:34.110 --> 00:54:37.930
that Einstein added
this term his equations.

00:54:37.930 --> 00:54:43.480
So the energy density of
the vacuum-- which is also

00:54:43.480 --> 00:54:45.460
the mass density of
the vacuum times c

00:54:45.460 --> 00:54:53.790
squared-- is equal to Einstein's
lambda times c to the fourth,

00:54:53.790 --> 00:55:01.050
over 8 pi G.

00:55:01.050 --> 00:55:03.680
And this is really just
an historical accident

00:55:03.680 --> 00:55:04.840
that it's defined this way.

00:55:04.840 --> 00:55:06.673
But this is the way
Einstein defined lambda.

00:55:11.780 --> 00:55:15.910
Now, if the vacuum
has an energy density,

00:55:15.910 --> 00:55:19.370
as the universe
expands the space

00:55:19.370 --> 00:55:20.640
is still filled with vacuum.

00:55:20.640 --> 00:55:22.400
At least, if it was
filled with vacuum.

00:55:22.400 --> 00:55:24.174
If it was matter
it would thin out.

00:55:24.174 --> 00:55:26.590
But we can imagine a region
of space that was just vacuum,

00:55:26.590 --> 00:55:29.360
and as it expands it would
have to just stay vacuum.

00:55:29.360 --> 00:55:31.850
What else could it become?

00:55:31.850 --> 00:55:35.110
And that means that we
know that, for a vacuum,

00:55:35.110 --> 00:55:39.250
rho dot should equal zero.

00:55:39.250 --> 00:55:43.170
Now we've also learned earlier,
by applying conservation

00:55:43.170 --> 00:55:46.270
of energy to the
expanding universe,

00:55:46.270 --> 00:55:54.680
that rho dot in an expanding
universe, is equal to minus 3

00:55:54.680 --> 00:55:56.280
a dot over a.

00:55:56.280 --> 00:56:00.650
Or we could write
this as h times

00:56:00.650 --> 00:56:04.065
rho plus p over c squared.

00:56:07.820 --> 00:56:10.710
This is basically
a rewriting of d u

00:56:10.710 --> 00:56:16.380
equals minus p d v, applying
it to the expanding universe.

00:56:16.380 --> 00:56:17.380
So I won't re-derive it.

00:56:17.380 --> 00:56:19.629
We already derived it.

00:56:19.629 --> 00:56:21.670
Actually, I think you
derived it on the homework,

00:56:21.670 --> 00:56:23.070
was the way it actually worked.

00:56:23.070 --> 00:56:26.090
But in any case,
this immediately

00:56:26.090 --> 00:56:33.680
tells us that if
rho dot is going

00:56:33.680 --> 00:56:47.530
to be 0 for vacuum
energy, this has to be 0.

00:56:47.530 --> 00:56:55.860
And therefore p vacuum has
to be equal to minus rho

00:56:55.860 --> 00:56:58.620
vacuum times c squared.

00:57:15.060 --> 00:57:17.260
And if we know the energy
density in the pressure

00:57:17.260 --> 00:57:20.174
of this stuff called
vacuum, that's

00:57:20.174 --> 00:57:22.590
all we need to know to put it
into the Friedmann equations

00:57:22.590 --> 00:57:25.370
and find out how things behave.

00:57:25.370 --> 00:57:27.660
Otherwise this vacuum energy
behaves no differently

00:57:27.660 --> 00:57:28.640
from anything else.

00:57:28.640 --> 00:57:31.090
It just has a
particular relationship

00:57:31.090 --> 00:57:34.700
between the pressure
and the energy density,

00:57:34.700 --> 00:57:37.455
with a very peculiar feature-
that the pressure is negative.

00:57:43.550 --> 00:57:45.300
And that's an important
feature because we

00:57:45.300 --> 00:57:47.660
had commented earlier that
a negative pressure can

00:57:47.660 --> 00:57:50.280
drive acceleration.

00:57:50.280 --> 00:57:55.490
And now we're in a good position
to see exactly how that works.

00:58:11.566 --> 00:58:13.690
To sort of keep
things straight I'm

00:58:13.690 --> 00:58:20.060
going to divide the mass
density of the universe

00:58:20.060 --> 00:58:26.105
into a vacuum piece
and a normal piece,

00:58:26.105 --> 00:58:30.100
where normal represents matter,
or radiation, or anything else,

00:58:30.100 --> 00:58:32.662
if we ever discover
something else.

00:58:32.662 --> 00:58:34.620
But in fact it will just
be matter or radiation

00:58:34.620 --> 00:58:36.190
for anything that we'll
be doing in this course,

00:58:36.190 --> 00:58:38.356
or anything that's really
done in current cosmology.

00:58:42.000 --> 00:58:48.100
And similarly, I'm going to
write pressure as p vac plus p

00:58:48.100 --> 00:58:48.830
normal.

00:58:48.830 --> 00:58:49.690
"N" is for normal.

00:58:55.800 --> 00:58:57.800
But p vac I don't
really need to use,

00:58:57.800 --> 00:59:01.589
because p vac I can rewrite
in terms of rho vac.

00:59:01.589 --> 00:59:03.380
So in the end I can
express everything just

00:59:03.380 --> 00:59:06.290
in terms of rho vac.

00:59:06.290 --> 00:59:09.650
And I can write down the second
order Friedmann equation.

00:59:14.537 --> 00:59:16.620
And it's just a matter of
substituting in that rho

00:59:16.620 --> 00:59:19.640
and that p into the
Friedmann equation

00:59:19.640 --> 00:59:21.430
that we've already written.

00:59:26.130 --> 00:59:34.960
And we get minus 4 pi
over 3 G, times rho

00:59:34.960 --> 00:59:42.730
normal plus 3 p
normal, over c squared.

00:59:42.730 --> 00:59:45.890
And the vacuum pieces-- have two
pieces because there's a vacuum

00:59:45.890 --> 00:59:49.730
piece there and a
vacuum piece there. it

00:59:49.730 --> 00:59:53.290
can all be expressed in terms
of rho vac and collected.

00:59:53.290 --> 01:00:02.650
And what you get is
minus 2 rho vac times a.

01:00:06.834 --> 01:00:08.500
Showing just what we
were talking about.

01:00:08.500 --> 01:00:10.700
That because of that minus
sign, multiplies that

01:00:10.700 --> 01:00:17.790
minus sign, vacuum energy drives
acceleration, not deceleration.

01:00:17.790 --> 01:00:20.640
And that's why vacuum
energy can explain

01:00:20.640 --> 01:00:23.810
these famous results of 1998.

01:00:23.810 --> 01:00:26.110
And we'll see later that,
for the same reason vacuum

01:00:26.110 --> 01:00:28.690
energy or things
like vacuum energy

01:00:28.690 --> 01:00:30.700
can actually drive the
expansion of the universe

01:00:30.700 --> 01:00:33.320
in the first place in
what we call inflation.

01:00:36.320 --> 01:00:37.130
Yes?

01:00:37.130 --> 01:00:39.950
AUDIENCE: So for the equation
without the cosmological

01:00:39.950 --> 01:00:46.110
constant it's, let's say, rho
and p are about the constant,

01:00:46.110 --> 01:00:48.054
then wouldn't that
be the equation

01:00:48.054 --> 01:00:50.000
for a simple harmonic
function [INAUDIBLE]

01:00:50.000 --> 01:00:54.546
or the oscillation
of a [INAUDIBLE]

01:00:54.546 --> 01:00:56.981
is some negative
constant times a?

01:00:59.910 --> 01:01:04.880
PROFESSOR: That's right, except
that you would probably not

01:01:04.880 --> 01:01:06.949
believe the equations
with the bounds.

01:01:06.949 --> 01:01:07.490
AUDIENCE: OK.

01:01:07.490 --> 01:01:09.781
PROFESSOR: And when a went
negative you wouldn't really

01:01:09.781 --> 01:01:11.880
have a cosmological
interpretation anymore,

01:01:11.880 --> 01:01:12.970
I don't think.

01:01:12.970 --> 01:01:17.340
But it is, in fact, true that
if rho and p were constants--

01:01:17.340 --> 01:01:20.360
I'm not sure of any model that
actually does that-- this would

01:01:20.360 --> 01:01:24.640
give you sinusoidal behavior
during the expanding

01:01:24.640 --> 01:01:27.670
and contracting phase.

01:01:27.670 --> 01:01:28.613
Yes?

01:01:28.613 --> 01:01:32.960
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE] the vacuum
energy is constant over time,

01:01:32.960 --> 01:01:36.867
is it also makes
sense [INAUDIBLE]?

01:01:36.867 --> 01:01:38.700
AUDIENCE: Are you asking,
does it make sense

01:01:38.700 --> 01:01:40.970
for maybe the vacuum
energy to change with time?

01:01:48.055 --> 01:01:49.430
I think, if it
changed with time,

01:01:49.430 --> 01:01:51.900
you wouldn't call
it vacuum energy.

01:01:51.900 --> 01:01:54.070
Because the vacuum
is more or less

01:01:54.070 --> 01:01:55.870
defined as the lowest
possible energy

01:01:55.870 --> 01:02:00.130
state allowed by
the laws of physics.

01:02:00.130 --> 01:02:02.210
And the laws of physics,
as far as we know,

01:02:02.210 --> 01:02:03.481
do not change with time.

01:02:03.481 --> 01:02:05.980
It's certainly true that, in a
completely different context,

01:02:05.980 --> 01:02:08.630
you might imagine the laws of
physics might change with time.

01:02:08.630 --> 01:02:10.700
And then thing would
get more complicated.

01:02:10.700 --> 01:02:13.580
But that would really take you
somewhat outside the sphere

01:02:13.580 --> 01:02:16.910
of physics as we know it.

01:02:16.910 --> 01:02:18.660
You could always explore
things like that,

01:02:18.660 --> 01:02:21.170
and it may turn out to be right.

01:02:21.170 --> 01:02:24.940
But at least within
the context of physics

01:02:24.940 --> 01:02:27.500
as we currently envision
it, vacuum energies

01:02:27.500 --> 01:02:29.280
are constant, pretty
much by definition.

01:02:35.920 --> 01:02:39.940
Now I should maybe qualify
that within the context of what

01:02:39.940 --> 01:02:45.650
we understand, there may,
in fact, be multiple vacua.

01:02:45.650 --> 01:02:48.740
For example, if you
have a field theory

01:02:48.740 --> 01:02:51.350
one can have a potential
energy function

01:02:51.350 --> 01:02:53.830
for one or more fields.

01:02:53.830 --> 01:02:55.280
And that potential
energy function

01:02:55.280 --> 01:02:58.680
could have more than
one local minimum.

01:02:58.680 --> 01:03:03.080
And then any one of those local
minima is effectively a vacuum.

01:03:03.080 --> 01:03:06.130
And that could very
likely be the situation

01:03:06.130 --> 01:03:07.970
that describes the real world.

01:03:07.970 --> 01:03:10.820
And then you could
tunnel from one vacuum

01:03:10.820 --> 01:03:13.990
to another, changing
the vacuum energy.

01:03:13.990 --> 01:03:15.890
But that would not be
a smooth evolution.

01:03:15.890 --> 01:03:17.350
That would be a
sudden tunneling.

01:03:33.490 --> 01:03:33.990
OK.

01:03:33.990 --> 01:03:37.120
So this is what happens to
the second order Friedmann

01:03:37.120 --> 01:03:39.576
equation.

01:03:39.576 --> 01:03:42.890
It is also very useful to look
at the first order Friedmann

01:03:42.890 --> 01:04:03.380
equation, which is a dot over
a squared, 8 pi over 3 G.

01:04:03.380 --> 01:04:08.970
And in its native
way of being written

01:04:08.970 --> 01:04:11.990
we would just have
8 pi over 3 G rho,

01:04:11.990 --> 01:04:16.100
minus k over-- kc
squared over a squared.

01:04:16.100 --> 01:04:20.450
And all I want to do now
is replace rho by rho

01:04:20.450 --> 01:04:21.690
vac plus rho n.

01:04:39.770 --> 01:04:41.670
And this is a first
order Friedmann equation.

01:04:47.450 --> 01:04:54.530
And we can expand rho n
if we want more details,

01:04:54.530 --> 01:04:59.070
as rho matter plus
rho radiation.

01:05:01.650 --> 01:05:07.940
And rho matter, we know,
varies with time proportional

01:05:07.940 --> 01:05:09.135
to 1 over a cubed.

01:05:12.710 --> 01:05:18.250
Rho radiation behaves with
time as 1 over a to the fourth.

01:05:21.020 --> 01:05:23.900
So all of the terms
here, except for rho vac,

01:05:23.900 --> 01:05:25.460
fall off as a grows.

01:05:28.200 --> 01:05:33.760
And that implies that
if you're not somehow

01:05:33.760 --> 01:05:35.889
turned around firsts,
which you can be--

01:05:35.889 --> 01:05:37.430
you could have a
closed universe that

01:05:37.430 --> 01:05:41.840
collapses before vacuum
energy can take over.

01:05:41.840 --> 01:05:47.430
But as the universe gets larger,
if it doesn't turn around,

01:05:47.430 --> 01:05:49.974
eventually rho vac will win.

01:05:49.974 --> 01:05:51.640
It will become larger
than anything else

01:05:51.640 --> 01:05:53.660
because everything else is just
getting smaller and smaller.

01:05:53.660 --> 01:05:55.576
And once that starts to
happen everything else

01:05:55.576 --> 01:05:57.930
will get smaller and
smaller, faster and faster,

01:05:57.930 --> 01:06:03.350
because a will start
to grow exponentially.

01:06:03.350 --> 01:06:17.140
If rho vac dominates--
which it will, as I said,

01:06:17.140 --> 01:06:18.890
unless the universe
re-collapses first--

01:06:18.890 --> 01:06:21.620
so for a large class
of solutions rho vac

01:06:21.620 --> 01:06:27.740
will dominate-- then you
can solve that equation.

01:06:27.740 --> 01:06:39.460
And you have h, which is
a dot over a, approaches,

01:06:39.460 --> 01:06:49.255
as a goes to infinity, the
square root of 8 pi over 3 G

01:06:49.255 --> 01:06:49.755
rho vac.

01:07:02.230 --> 01:07:09.250
So h will approach a fixed
value for a universe which

01:07:09.250 --> 01:07:13.540
is ultimately dominated
by rho vacuum.

01:07:13.540 --> 01:07:15.260
And if a dot over
a is a constant,

01:07:15.260 --> 01:07:16.845
that means that a
grows exponentially.

01:08:06.800 --> 01:08:10.840
So we could maybe give
this a name-- h vac.

01:08:10.840 --> 01:08:12.680
The value h has
when it's completely

01:08:12.680 --> 01:08:15.890
dominated by the vacuum energy.

01:08:15.890 --> 01:08:30.485
And then we can
write that a of t

01:08:30.485 --> 01:08:35.090
is ultimately going to be
proportional to e to the h vac

01:08:35.090 --> 01:08:36.557
times t.

01:08:36.557 --> 01:08:38.640
Which is what you get when
you solve the equation,

01:08:38.640 --> 01:08:40.760
a dot over a equals
this constant.

01:08:53.520 --> 01:08:54.479
OK.

01:08:54.479 --> 01:09:00.485
Now one thing which you
can see very quickly--

01:09:00.485 --> 01:09:02.359
let's see how far I
should plan to get today.

01:09:20.220 --> 01:09:20.720
OK.

01:09:20.720 --> 01:09:22.511
I'll probably make one
qualitative argument

01:09:22.511 --> 01:09:25.399
and then start a calculation
that won't get very far.

01:09:25.399 --> 01:09:27.680
I will continue next time.

01:09:27.680 --> 01:09:29.750
One qualitative
point which you can

01:09:29.750 --> 01:09:33.710
see from just glancing
at these equations

01:09:33.710 --> 01:09:37.950
is that the cosmological
constant, when

01:09:37.950 --> 01:09:40.330
added to the other
ingredients that we've already

01:09:40.330 --> 01:09:42.779
put into our model
universe, will

01:09:42.779 --> 01:09:45.550
have the effect of
increasing the age

01:09:45.550 --> 01:09:48.950
of the universe for
a given value of h.

01:09:48.950 --> 01:09:52.410
And that's something that we
said earlier in the course,

01:09:52.410 --> 01:09:53.910
we're looking forward to.

01:09:53.910 --> 01:09:56.460
Because the model of
the universe that we're

01:09:56.460 --> 01:09:58.420
been constructing
so far have always

01:09:58.420 --> 01:10:04.359
turned out to be too young
for the measured value of h.

01:10:04.359 --> 01:10:06.150
That is, the oldest
stars look like they're

01:10:06.150 --> 01:10:07.310
older than the universe.

01:10:07.310 --> 01:10:08.370
And that's not good.

01:10:08.370 --> 01:10:11.030
So we'd like to make
universe look older.

01:10:11.030 --> 01:10:17.460
And one of the beauties of
having this vacuum energy,

01:10:17.460 --> 01:10:19.120
as far as making
things fit together,

01:10:19.120 --> 01:10:21.410
is that it does make
the universe older.

01:10:21.410 --> 01:10:26.050
And the easiest way to
see that-- at least a way

01:10:26.050 --> 01:10:32.530
to see that-- is to imagine
drawing a graph of h versus t.

01:10:32.530 --> 01:10:36.320
Hubble expansion rate versus t.

01:10:36.320 --> 01:10:40.510
And if we look at
the formula for h

01:10:40.510 --> 01:10:44.770
here we see that the
rho vac piece just

01:10:44.770 --> 01:10:49.800
puts in a floor as
h evolves with time,

01:10:49.800 --> 01:10:53.420
instead of going to 0 as it
wood in most models-- at least,

01:10:53.420 --> 01:10:56.250
as it would in
open-universe model.

01:10:56.250 --> 01:10:57.855
It stops at some floor.

01:11:00.560 --> 01:11:11.050
And certainly for the models
that we've been dealing with,

01:11:11.050 --> 01:11:15.370
h just decreases to
some-- this is supposed

01:11:15.370 --> 01:11:18.650
to represent the present time.

01:11:18.650 --> 01:11:24.115
So this is previous models.

01:11:27.852 --> 01:11:30.310
Now as you might say, that what
I'm trying to describe here

01:11:30.310 --> 01:11:35.220
is not quite a theorem if you
considered closed universes

01:11:35.220 --> 01:11:43.471
where this k piece
could be causing

01:11:43.471 --> 01:11:47.010
a positive-- a negative
contribution to h, which

01:11:47.010 --> 01:11:48.640
is then decreasing with time.

01:11:48.640 --> 01:11:50.674
Things can get complicated.

01:11:50.674 --> 01:11:52.840
But for the models that
we've been considering which

01:11:52.840 --> 01:11:57.130
are nearly flat, that
k piece is absent.

01:11:57.130 --> 01:12:00.660
And then we just have pieces
that go like, 1 over a cubed,

01:12:00.660 --> 01:12:03.060
1 over a to the
fourth, and constant.

01:12:03.060 --> 01:12:05.650
All of which are positive.

01:12:05.650 --> 01:12:11.920
Then in the absence of vacuum
energy we would have h falling.

01:12:11.920 --> 01:12:16.270
And with the presence
of vacuum energy

01:12:16.270 --> 01:12:17.820
it would not fall
as fast because we

01:12:17.820 --> 01:12:21.890
have this constant piece
that would not be decreasing.

01:12:21.890 --> 01:12:24.110
So this is previous models.

01:12:24.110 --> 01:12:29.780
This is with rho vac.

01:12:29.780 --> 01:12:32.340
And I'm always talking
about positive rho vac

01:12:32.340 --> 01:12:34.800
because that is what
our universe has.

01:12:38.307 --> 01:12:40.140
So this would be the
two different behaviors

01:12:40.140 --> 01:12:46.110
of h for the model
without vacuum energy

01:12:46.110 --> 01:12:48.140
and the model with
vacuum energy.

01:12:48.140 --> 01:12:51.170
And if we're trying to calculate
the age of the universe

01:12:51.170 --> 01:12:53.900
we would basically be
extrapolating this curve back

01:12:53.900 --> 01:12:57.410
to the point where h was
infinite, at the big bang.

01:12:57.410 --> 01:12:59.900
And we could see that,
since this curve is always

01:12:59.900 --> 01:13:01.750
below this curve,
it will take longer

01:13:01.750 --> 01:13:05.140
before it turns up
and becomes infinite.

01:13:05.140 --> 01:13:10.886
So the age will always increase
by adding vacuum energy.

01:13:22.310 --> 01:13:34.500
With rho vac h equals infinity
is further to the left.

01:13:38.902 --> 01:13:41.110
And notice that I'm comparing
two different theories,

01:13:41.110 --> 01:13:42.651
both of which are
the same age today.

01:13:42.651 --> 01:13:44.920
Because that's what
we're interested in.

01:13:44.920 --> 01:13:46.170
We've measured the value of h.

01:13:46.170 --> 01:13:48.475
We're trying to infer
the age of the universe.

01:14:02.450 --> 01:14:02.950
OK.

01:14:02.950 --> 01:14:05.283
Maybe I'll just say a couple
words about the calculation

01:14:05.283 --> 01:14:07.242
that we'll be starting
with next time.

01:14:07.242 --> 01:14:08.950
We want to be able to
precisely calculate

01:14:08.950 --> 01:14:10.490
things like the age
of the universe,

01:14:10.490 --> 01:14:13.340
including the effect
of this vacuum energy.

01:14:13.340 --> 01:14:16.840
And we'll be able to do that
in a very straightforward way

01:14:16.840 --> 01:14:19.165
by using this first
order Friedmann equation.

01:14:22.180 --> 01:14:25.100
We know how each term in
this Friedmann equation

01:14:25.100 --> 01:14:28.240
varies with a.

01:14:28.240 --> 01:14:30.227
And we can measure
the amount of matter,

01:14:30.227 --> 01:14:32.560
and the amount of radiation,
and in principal the amount

01:14:32.560 --> 01:14:35.030
of curvature-- it's
negligibly small--

01:14:35.030 --> 01:14:37.480
in our current universe.

01:14:37.480 --> 01:14:40.600
And once you have
those parameters

01:14:40.600 --> 01:14:43.070
you can use that
equation to extrapolate,

01:14:43.070 --> 01:14:47.020
to know what h was at
any time in the past.

01:14:47.020 --> 01:14:51.990
And that tells you
how the derivative--

01:14:51.990 --> 01:14:55.820
it tells you the value of a
dot at any time in the past.

01:14:55.820 --> 01:14:58.670
And if you know the value of
a dot at any time in the past,

01:14:58.670 --> 01:15:01.080
it's a principle just
a matter of integration

01:15:01.080 --> 01:15:04.330
to figure out when a was 0.

01:15:04.330 --> 01:15:07.710
And that's the calculation that
we'll begin by doing next time.

01:15:07.710 --> 01:15:11.020
And we'll be able to get
an integral expression

01:15:11.020 --> 01:15:14.980
for the age of the universe
for an arbitrary value.

01:15:14.980 --> 01:15:18.180
We'll, at the end,
express the matter density

01:15:18.180 --> 01:15:20.710
and the radiation
density as fractions

01:15:20.710 --> 01:15:24.470
of omega, fractions of
the critical density.

01:15:24.470 --> 01:15:27.480
And for any value
of omega matter,

01:15:27.480 --> 01:15:30.810
omega radiation, and we'll
even express the curvature

01:15:30.810 --> 01:15:31.920
as an omega curvature.

01:15:31.920 --> 01:15:34.040
The effective fraction
of the critical density

01:15:34.040 --> 01:15:36.120
that this term represents.

01:15:36.120 --> 01:15:38.075
And in terms of those
different omegas,

01:15:38.075 --> 01:15:39.700
we'll be able to
write down an integral

01:15:39.700 --> 01:15:42.080
for the total age
of the universe.

01:15:42.080 --> 01:15:44.100
And that really is going
to be state of the art.

01:15:44.100 --> 01:15:48.160
That is what the
Planck team uses

01:15:48.160 --> 01:15:50.854
when they're analyzing their
data to try to understand what

01:15:50.854 --> 01:15:53.020
the age of universe is
according to the measurements

01:15:53.020 --> 01:15:55.180
that they're making.

01:15:55.180 --> 01:15:59.180
So we will finally come
up to the present as far

01:15:59.180 --> 01:16:05.210
as the actual understanding
of cosmology by the experts.

01:16:05.210 --> 01:16:07.530
So that's all for today.

01:16:07.530 --> 01:16:10.000
see you all next Tuesday.

